{#
  Jellyfin core branding config (BrandingOptions -> /config/config/branding.xml).
  The SSO plugin has no native login button; the documented way to add one
  is to inject an HTML <form> into the "Login disclaimer", which the web
  client renders on the sign-in page. The form GETs the plugin's
  /sso/OID/start/<provider> endpoint to begin the OIDC flow.

  The HTML must be entity-escaped here because LoginDisclaimer is a string
  field: .NET's XmlSerializer stores it escaped and the web client
  unescapes + injects it. Jellyfin only rewrites this file on a dashboard
  save, so DO NOT edit branding via the Jellyfin UI -- manage it here.
  See notes/jellyfin_sso_rollout.md.

  CustomCss hides every native web-login affordance (the user-avatar
  picker, the Manual Login button + its username/password form, and
  Forgot Password), leaving only the SSO button above -- Jellyfin has no
  server-side toggle to disable password login. This is web-UI only:
  native apps + Quick Connect still authenticate via the API, and the
  local break-glass admin remains reachable by re-applying this role with
  an empty CustomCss (no Authelia dependency) or via browser devtools.
#}
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<BrandingOptions xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xmlns:xsd="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema">
  <LoginDisclaimer>&lt;form action="https://jellyfin.{{ inventory_hostname }}.{{ domain }}/sso/OID/start/authelia"&gt;&lt;button class="raised block emby-button button-submit"&gt;Sign in with SSO&lt;/button&gt;&lt;/form&gt;</LoginDisclaimer>
  <CustomCss>.manualLoginForm, .visualLoginForm, .btnManual, .btnForgotPassword { display: none !important; }</CustomCss>
  <SplashscreenEnabled>false</SplashscreenEnabled>
</BrandingOptions>
